Title: Heavy-Tailed Phenomena in Combinatorial Search  
Author: Carla P. Gomes Bart Selman and Nuno Crato 
Abstract: Randomized search methods have greatly extended our ability to solve hard computational problems. However, these methods often exhibit a surprisingly large variability in performance. In particular, the solution time for different runs on the same problem instance can vary over several orders of magnitude, and is thus highly unpredictable. We explore this phenomenon by studying the cost profiles of search techniques on hard combinatorial problems. Our results reveal intriguing properties of such profiles: the distributions are characterized by heavy tails of the Pareto-Levy form with infinite moments. Such non-standard distributions are closely related to fractal phenomena, and have been observed in areas as diverse as economics, statistical physics, and geophysics. Our work is the first finding of these distributions in a pure computational setting. The heavy-tailed nature of computational phenomena explains some puzzling behavior of the cost profiles, which have been discussed and documented in the literature. In addition, it explains the effectiveness of various recent algorithmic strategies used in solving combinatorial problems, and suggests the design of other more efficient search strategies.
